05429nam a22006975i 9780824860776DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248607767 a10.1515/97808248607762doi  a(DE-B1597)483932  a(OCoLC)1024040995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aGF666b.K57 2011 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a304.209522221 aKirby, Peter Wynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTroubled Natures :bWaste, Environment, Japan /cPeter Wynn Kirby. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b14 b&w images, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction: Japan’s Waste Shadow -- tChapter 2. Perils of Proximity: An Invisible Scourge -- tChapter 3. Mediated Anxieties: Nowhere to Hide -- tChapter 4. The Cult(ures) of Japanese Nature -- tChapter 5. Tokyo’s Vermin Menace -- tChapter 6. Pure Obsession: Pollution, Outcasts, and Exclusion -- tChapter 7. Growth, Sex, Fertility, and Decline -- tChapter 8. Constructing Sustainable Japan -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does "environment" really mean in the complex, non-Western milieu of present-day Tokyo? How can anthropology contribute to the technical discussions and quantitative measures typically found in environmental studies? Author Peter Wynn Kirby explores these questions through a deep cultural analysis of waste in contemporary Japan. His parameters are intentionally broad—encompassing ideas of "nature," attitudes toward hygiene, notions of health and illness, problems with vermin and toxic waste, processes of social exclusion, and reproductive threats. Troubled Natures concludes that how surroundings are conceived, invoked, and enacted is subjective, highly contextual, and under continual negotiation—with suggestive implications for anthropology, social science, and environmental studies generally.Kirby casts his anthropological lens over two Tokyo neighborhoods, comparing environmental consciousness and conduct in communities facing specific toxic threats (real or perceived). In each fieldsite, the tension between lofty rhetoric and daily practices helps highlight the practical ambivalence of Japanese environmental consciousness. Waste practices and ideas of pollution in Tokyo tie clearly into broader social issues such as exclusionary practices, emergent lifestyle changes, recycling efforts, and novel forms of energy production. Throughout, waste and environmental health problems in Tokyo collide against diverse cultural elements linked to nature(s)—uneasy relations between animals and humans; "native" conceptions of the "foreign" and the "polluted"; reproductive challenges in the face of a plunging fertility rate; and changing attitudes toward illness and health. The book’s thoughtful inquiry into the ways in which environmental questions circulate throughout Japanese society furnishes insight into central elements of contemporary Japanese life.As for the pivotal question of how to shape environmental policy internationally, Troubled Natures reminds us that efforts to influence a society’s waste shadow must unfold over a distinctive sociocultural topography where attitudes to garbage, health, purity, pollution, and excess can impact environmental priorities in profound ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman ecologyzJapan. 0aPollutionzJapanxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzJapan. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology)zJapanzTokyo. 0aWaste productszJapanxPublic opinion. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Prote